==English==
{{wikipedia|dab=bind}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang}} ''[[bindan]]'', from {{proto|Germanic|bindanan}} (compare West Frisian {{term|bine|lang=fy}}, Dutch/German ''[[binden]]''), from {{proto|Indo-European|bhendh-}} 'to tie' (compare Welsh {{term|benn|lang=cy}} 'cart', Latin {{term|offendix|offendīx|lang=la}} 'knot, band', Lithuanian {{term|beñdras|lang=lt}} 'partner', Albanian {{term|bend||servant,henchman|lang=sq}}, {{term|bind||to convince, persuade, tame|lang=sq}}, Ancient Greek {{term|πεῖσμα|tr=peisma||cable, rope|lang=grc}}, Sanskrit {{term|badhnāti}}{{rfscript|Devanagari|lang=sa}} 'he binds').

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/baɪnd/}}
* {{audio|en-us-bind.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|aɪnd}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# That which binds or ties.
# A [[troublesome]] situation; a [[problem]]; a [[predicament]] or [[quandary]].
# Any twining or climbing plant or stem, especially a [[hop]] vine; a [[bine]].
# {{music}} A [[ligature]] or [[tie]] for grouping notes.

====Synonyms====
* See also [[Wikisaurus:difficult situation]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb|binds|binding|bound|'''[[bound]]''' ''or rarely'' '''[[bounden]]'''}}

# {{intransitive}} To tie; to confine by any [[ligature]].
#* {{rfdate}} {{w|Shakespeare}}
#*: They that reap must sheaf and '''bind'''.
# {{intransitive}} To cohere or stick together in a mass.
#: ''Just to make the cheese more '''binding'''
#* {{rfdate}} {{w|Mortimer}}
#*: clay '''binds''' by heat.
# {{intransitive}} To be restrained from motion, or from customary or natural action, as by friction.
#: ''I wish I knew why the sewing machine '''binds''' up after I use it for a while.''
# To exert a binding or restraining influence.
#: These are the ties that '''bind'''.''
# {{transitive}} To [[tie]] or [[fasten]] tightly together.
# {{transitive}} To [[couple]].
# {{transitive}} To put together in a cover, as of books.
# {{transitive|computing}} To associate an [[identifier]] with a value; to associate a variable name with the content of a storage location. {{rfex}}

